HEADWORD: Torso
<hw>Tor"so</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E.
<plw>Torsos</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, It. <plw>Torsi</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[It. <ets>torso</ets>, probably fr. L. <ets>thyrsus</ets> a stalk,
stem, thyrsus, Gr. <?/; cf. OHG. <ets>torso</ets>, <ets>turso</ets>, a
stalk, stem, G. <ets>dorsche</ets> a cabbage stalk. Cf.
<er>Thyrsus</er>, <er>Truss</er>.]</ety> <def>The human body, as
distinguished from the head and limbs; in sculpture, the trunk of a
statue, mutilated of head and limbs; <as>as, the <ex>torso</ex> of
Hercules</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

